    "author": "Kevin Studley",
    "product_type": "summary",
    "bottom_line": "<p class=\"afp-html-p\">Human <a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/trigger\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A disturbance that initiates fracture within the weak layer causing an avalanche. In 90 percent of avalanche accidents, the victim or someone in the victims party triggers the avalanche.\">triggered</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanches</a> remain possible.&nbsp; Multiple weak <a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a>&nbsp;exist in the upper two to three feet of the snowpack.&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/persistent-weak-layers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Avalanche problem caused by weak layers buried in the snowpack that can produce avalanches for several days or weeks after a storm.\">Persistent slab</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanches</a>&nbsp;will be difficult to&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/trigger\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A disturbance that initiates fracture within the weak layer causing an avalanche. In 90 percent of avalanche accidents, the victim or someone in the victims party triggers the avalanche.\">trigger</a>&nbsp;but the size would be destructive. The weight of a snowmachine is more likely to impact these deeper weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a>&nbsp;than the weight of a person.</p>\n<p class=\"afp-html-p\">Small, wind&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/slab\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A relatively cohesive snowpack layer.\">slab</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanches</a> remain possible today with the recent storm snow and strong winds from Saturday/Sunday. You may find sensitive wind deposited snow at or near ridgelines. Watch for clues that indicate wind direction and pay attention to how the snow changes with the terrain.&nbsp;</p>",
    "hazard_discussion": "<p>Although yesterday's advisory read moderate, this is a different kind of moderate than what we've been dealing with over the past few months. Since early January, we have experienced little in terms of significant snow. Over the past few months, the <a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanche</a>&nbsp;hazard would rise and fall in conjunction with incoming storms. You may remember reading about shallow wind&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/slab\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A relatively cohesive snowpack layer.\">slab</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanches</a> and dry or wet loose avalanches. Within the past week, <strong>we are now dealing with a different type of moderate</strong>. This is when it's time to pay closer attention to the&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanche</a> problems. A&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/persistent-weak-layers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Avalanche problem caused by weak layers buried in the snowpack that can produce avalanches for several days or weeks after a storm.\">persistent slab problem</a>&nbsp;presents different challenges than a wind&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/slab\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A relatively cohesive snowpack layer.\">slab</a>&nbsp;or dry loose avalanche.&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/persistent-weak-layers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Avalanche problem caused by weak layers buried in the snowpack that can produce avalanches for several days or weeks after a storm.\">Persistent slabs</a>&nbsp;are more difficult to&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/trigger\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A disturbance that initiates fracture within the weak layer causing an avalanche. In 90 percent of avalanche accidents, the victim or someone in the victims party triggers the avalanche.\">trigger</a> and are much more destructive. They are much more difficult to predict. These buried weak <a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a>&nbsp;lurk under feet of snow and can make it seem as they are not present most of the time. Now is a good time to be digging into the snow. Take a few moments to look for these buried weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a>&nbsp;and see if they exist in the particular terrain you are wanting to recreate in. I would be alert to activity on buried weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a>&nbsp;on slopes below 7800' that face east through west on the northern half of the compass. You are more likely to experience&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/collapse\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"When the fracture of a lower snow layer causes an upper layer to fall. Also called a whumpf, this is an obvious sign of instability.\">collapsing</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/whumpf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"When the fracture of a lower snow layer causes an upper layer to fall or collapse, making a whumpfing sound. This an obvious sign of instability. See Collapse.\">whumpfing</a>&nbsp;than you are shooting cracks.&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/collapse\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"When the fracture of a lower snow layer causes an upper layer to fall. Also called a whumpf, this is an obvious sign of instability.\">Collapsing</a>&nbsp;of a buried weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layer</a>&nbsp;is a red flag and you need to adjust your terrain selection accordingly if you experience any red flags.</p>\n<p class=\"afp-html-p\">In some locations, we have a decent&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/slab\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A relatively cohesive snowpack layer.\">slab</a>&nbsp;overlying a persistent weak layer. This weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layer</a>&nbsp;is composed of 1-1.5 mm&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/faceted-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Angular snow with poor bonding created from large temperature gradients within the snowpack.\">facets</a>&nbsp;sitting on or near the interface from the 03/01 storm that produced rain up 7800'. We have not seen a&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/persistent-weak-layers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Weak layers buried in the snowpack that can produce avalanches for several days or weeks after a storm.\">persistent weak layer</a>&nbsp;problem all season long. It may surprise people to be dealing with a&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/persistent-weak-layers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Weak layers buried in the snowpack that can produce avalanches for several days or weeks after a storm.\">persistent weak layer</a>&nbsp;problem this late in the season, but this problem warrants your attention. We have received multiple reports throughout our advisory area of reactivity on buried weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a> in our upper snowpack. With a little bit of new snow yesterday, there is additional stress on these weak layers.</p>\n<p class=\"afp-html-p\"><a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/trigger\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A disturbance that initiates fracture within the weak layer causing an avalanche. In 90 percent of avalanche accidents, the victim or someone in the victims party triggers the avalanche.\">Triggering</a>&nbsp;a&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/persistent-weak-layers\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"Avalanche problem caused by weak layers buried in the snowpack that can produce avalanches for several days or weeks after a storm.\">persistent slab</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanche</a>&nbsp;will be difficult unless you find a shallow spot in the snowpack (<a class=\"afp-html-a\" title=\"Beaverdam snowpit talk\" href=\"https://youtu.be/8E6oyTrGDE0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">see video)</a>. However, the consequences are fairly high as an&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanche</a> would involve the top 2 feet of dense snow.&nbsp; There is a lot of variability with these persistent weak layers. The sensitivity may vary depending on <a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/aspect\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"The compass direction a slope faces (i.e. North, South, East, or West.)\">aspect</a>&nbsp;and elevation. Below 7800' exhibit caution on steeper slopes that face the northern half of the compass. Pay attention to&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/collapse\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"When the fracture of a lower snow layer causes an upper layer to fall. Also called a whumpf, this is an obvious sign of instability.\">collapsing</a>&nbsp;of weak&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/layer-snow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A snowpack stratum differentiated from others by weather, metamorphism, or other processes.\">layers</a>&nbsp;like the sounds of whumpfing. If you experience a collapse, stay off of steep slopes in that terrain.</p>\n<p>You can expect wind&nbsp;<a class=\"afp-glossary\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/slab\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A relatively cohesive snowpack layer.\">slabs</a> to become more reactive today. Our advisory area saw anywhere from 2-6 inches of snow Saturday night into Sunday morning. Winds were moderate to strong out of the W/SW Saturday afternoon. Sunday, the winds shifted out of the NW and eventually north. Wind-deposited snow could be up to a foot deep in some locations at or near ridgelines. Pay attention to visual clues near ridgelines and in areas where blowing snow may have been deposited.</p>",
